# Best Practice Map

Use this map to judge and improve all work.

## 1. Coding Best Practices

* Keep code modular.
* Do not repeat logic.
* Use reusable functions.
* Use clear names.
* Keep files focused.
* Add comments only where useful.
* Test before calling work complete.
* Protect existing working code.
* Use config files instead of hardcoded values.
* Keep rollback possible.

Example: If building a script, create one clean script, one config file, one validation method, one test command, and one usage guide instead of hardcoding everything into one large file.

## 2. Design Best Practices

* Keep layouts clean.
* Make important actions obvious.
* Remove clutter.
* Keep spacing consistent.
* Use consistent colors and typography.
* Design for clarity first.
* Make systems easy for new users to understand.

Example: A dashboard should separate primary actions, live status, history, logs, proof, alerts, and next actions.

## 3. Writing Best Practices

* Use plain language.
* Keep purpose obvious.
* Use strong titles.
* Break long ideas into sections.
* Remove vague wording.
* Keep next actions clear.
* Keep useful detail while removing noise.

Example: Every doc should answer what it is, why it matters, how it is used, what steps are required, and how we know it worked.

## 4. Repo Best Practices

* Every file has a clear home.
* Every folder has a purpose.
* No loose files.
* No duplicate versions without reason.
* Use naming standards.
* Use README files where needed.
* Track important decisions.
* Separate templates from live work.
* Separate drafts from production-ready systems.

Example: A reusable prompt template belongs in `/templates/prompts/`, not hidden inside random notes or scratch folders.

## 5. Git Safety Best Practices

* Check repo status before work.
* Create safe branches.
* Never overwrite unknown work.
* Review diffs before commit.
* Use clear commit messages.
* Keep rollback possible.
* Confirm clean repo state after work.

Example workflow: Check status → create branch → make changes → run tests → review diff → commit cleanly → confirm repo health.

## 6. Audit Best Practices

* Start with verified facts.
* List what was reviewed.
* Identify gaps clearly.
* Separate proof from opinion.
* Mark risks visibly.
* Create fix checklists.
* Keep findings traceable.

Example: An audit should include reviewed files, findings, risks, proof, fixes, owners, and completion status.

## 7. Investigation Best Practices

* Define the problem first.
* Gather evidence.
* Track sources.
* Separate facts from assumptions.
* Identify patterns.
* End with findings and next actions.

Example: Do not patch bugs blindly. Reproduce → inspect → isolate → fix → validate.

## 8. Problem-Solving Best Practices

* Identify root causes.
* Break problems into parts.
* Fix repeat causes.
* Build reusable solutions.
* Add safeguards to stop recurrence.

Example: If prompts repeatedly require cleanup, create reusable prompt standards, validation rules, cleanup automation, and formatting templates.

## 9. Automation Best Practices

* Automate repeated work.
* Keep automation safe.
* Use config-driven systems.
* Add logging.
* Add dry-run modes.
* Keep rollback possible.
* Make errors visible.

Example: A cleanup tool should preview changes, log changes, validate changes, and allow rollback.

## 10. AI Skill Best Practices

* One skill equals one clear responsibility.
* Clear trigger conditions.
* Defined outputs.
* Reusable rules.
* Organized support files.
* Validation included.
* Reduce future manual work.

Example: A Repo Auditor skill should know when to activate, what to inspect, what checklist to run, and what report to produce.

## 11. Documentation Best Practices

* Explain purpose clearly.
* Show file locations.
* Include examples.
* Include validation steps.
* Include recovery instructions.
* Keep documentation updated.

Example: A setup guide should include install, usage, testing, troubleshooting, and recovery.

## 12. Workflow Best Practices

* Define intake.
* Define goals.
* Gather inputs.
* Execute in stages.
* Validate each stage.
* File outputs properly.
* Record lessons learned.
* Convert repeated work into templates or automation.

Example: Every workflow should end with what changed, what was checked, where it was filed, and what improves next time.

## 13. Decision Best Practices

* Record decisions clearly.
* Explain why decisions were made.
* Record rejected options when useful.
* Make decisions reviewable later.

Example: If choosing a repo structure, document why it was chosen, what problem it solves, and what standards it supports.

## 14. Quality Best Practices

* Check for missing parts.
* Check for duplication.
* Check for unclear language.
* Check for broken paths.
* Confirm reusability.
* Confirm readiness before shipping.

Example: Before saying “done,” validate, test, organize, review, and confirm usability.

## 15. Filing Best Practices

* File by purpose.
* Keep drafts separate from finals.
* Use clear folder names.
* Keep important systems easy to locate.
* Keep archives organized.

Example: Final checklists belong in `/checklists/final/`, not mixed into scratch work.

## 16. Learning Best Practices

* Capture what worked.
* Capture what failed.
* Convert lessons into rules.
* Convert repeated tasks into templates.
* Convert manual work into automation.
* Convert mistakes into safeguards.

Example: Every hard problem solved should improve the repo permanently.

## 17. Safety Best Practices

* Never destroy working systems.
* Never skip backups.
* Never hide uncertainty.
* Never ship untested work.
* Always maintain recovery paths.

Example: Before large changes, backup, branch, validate, review, and confirm recoverability.

## 18. “God Mode” Best Practice Rule

When asked to improve, elevate, optimize, or go beyond the original request, do not only complete the obvious task.

Also identify:

* Missing systems
* Hidden risks
* Reusable upgrades
* Automation opportunities
* Filing improvements
* Workflow reductions
* Future-proofing opportunities
* Validation improvements
* Repo intelligence improvements
* Modular architecture opportunities
* Boolean lead sheet opportunities

Example: If improving a prompt, also improve structure, reusability, repo filing, validation, automation, safety, checklist conversion, upgrade paths, and future scaling support.

